The distance that a vehicle travels with a certain amount of fuel (i.e.,
F u C R
) depends on factors such as a vehicle, traffic, and traveling speed. In the proposed model, we use the average expected speed among nodes, therefore, the expected amount of fuel consumption is calculated. The calculation of the fuel consumption is based on Kuo (2010). Poonthalir and Nadarajan (2018) developed a similar FGVR using a triangular distribution. Besides, there are some similar studies in different ways (Hooshmand and MirHassani, 2019; Koç and Karaoglan, 2016; Xiao et al., 2012).

In this section, we begin our analysis by assessing the capability of metaheuristic algorithms to find solutions that are closely aligned with the optimal ones for Problem #4. This evaluation involves a comparison against benchmarks set by the results of a commercial solver. Subsequently, we leverage the predefined performance metrics to conduct an in-depth comparative analysis, comparing the metaheuristic algorithms against one another across a series of increasingly complex problem instances. The Hypervolume (HV) metric (Fig. 9
                           ) is utilized for this comparison, including against the commercial solver, and its results are illustrated in Fig. 10
                           .

The subsequent phase of the analysis examines the impact of the maximum route time, a factor of significant importance in the model, especially in terms of the operational decision-making timeframe. Fig. 16 illustrates the consequences of adjusting the maximum allowable time for routes (
T m a x
) on decision-making. A reduction in
T m a x
leads to a noticeable decrease in the average route time (
R T
). This, in turn, necessitates an increase in the number of routing vehicles (
Y
) used to fulfill the demands. This decrease in route time is likely to cause an increase in the first objective function (
Z 1
). In a similar vein, the second objective function (
Z 2
) is expected to rise due to the shorter travel times and the reduced number of stops per routing vehicle. Moreover, employing more vehicles correlates with more job creation, thereby enhancing the third objective function (
Z 3
).

The evaluation now focuses on assessing the impact of the maximum allowed vehicles of depots. This parameter stands as a sensitive parameter, exerting influence on various variables. Fig. 17 demonstrates the effect of maximum allowed number of allowed vehicles of each DC/CC (
A V
) on some variables. An increase in
A V
leads to a rise in the number of employed routing vehicles (i.e., Y). Interestingly, an inverse relationship is noticeable; as each DC/CC is capable of hiring more routing vehicles, the number of opened DC/CCs (i.e., SD) decreases. Consequently, the first objective function (i.e.,
Z 1
) experiences a downward trajectory. Meanwhile, the second objective function (i.e.,
Z 2
) shows marginal alterations. The reduction in the necessity for opened DC/CCs contributes to a decrease in the third objective function (i.e.,
Z 3
) and created career opportunities.

Next, the effect of created job opportunities by the establishment of a repair centers (
J o e
e h
) are analyzed and illustrated in Fig. 18 . As can be seen, by increasing
J o e
e h
, total created job opportunities will rise and the third objective function (i.e.,
Z 3
) will be enhanced, new repair centers will establish which are even more than the needs. Number of repairs centers (i.e.,
S E
) has increased while the number of recycling centers (i.e.,
S R
) is constant. The establishment of new repair centers has caused an increase in total costs and the first objective function (i.e.,
Z 1
). The second objective function (i.e.,
Z 2
) remains unchanged.

Finally, the relation between scenarios and objective functions, as sustainability goals, are analyzed. The scenarios, generated as outputs of the backward scenario reduction method, are essential components in our model as they approximate continuous probability distributions with discrete scenarios. In this analysis, we systematically varied the generated scenarios to understand their influence on the model outcomes. The results of this sensitivity analysis are presented in Fig. 19 , providing valuable insights into how changes in scenarios impact the performance of our proposed model. As can be seen in Fig. 19, two scenarios are generated using the backward scenario reduction method. In the first scenario, the total demand remains relatively stable. However, in the second scenario, the product rate of return is slightly higher than in the first scenario. Alongside alterations in distribution and collection planning, there are more items to collect in the second scenario. This increase in the number of returned products, coupled with changes in routing, leads to higher costs, fuel consumption, and an increased demand for recycling and repair centers. It is noteworthy that changes in distribution and collection planning, influenced by variations in demand and product rate of return, lead to more rapid alterations in the environmental objective function (i.e.,
Z 2
). Subsequently, the social objective function (i.e.,
Z 3
) experiences more pronounced changes compared to the economic objective function (i.e.,
Z 1
)
.
